properties.query:
// Contributor: Kamran Arshad
// Source:  https://redcanary.com/blog/detecting-and-mitigating-ransomware/ | and | https://servicedesk.costargroup.com/browse/SEC-4704
// Reviewer: Lucas Trainer
//
// Description: Detect PS with "DownloadString" in cmdline - this can be indicative of attempts to download and execute malicious code using native windows binaries. 
//
// Handling Guidance: Examine the user and download target to identify if this is a permitted activity, or a sign of post-exploitation behavior Also look at other activities performed by the user after this command was run to look for the signs of malicious activity. 
//
// Query: 
let ignore_targets = dynamic(["https://chocolatey.org/install.ps1","https://community.chocolatey.org/install.ps1"]);
DeviceEvents
| where InitiatingProcessFileName has "powershell.exe"
    and InitiatingProcessCommandLine has "DownloadString"
| extend DownloadTarget_ = extract_all(@"(?i:DownloadString[(])(.*)[)]", InitiatingProcessCommandLine)
| where not(DownloadTarget_ has_any (ignore_targets))
| extend Description_ =  strcat("The account ", InitiatingProcessAccountName, " executed a suspicious powershell command on ", DeviceName, ". The target file downloaded was located at: ", DownloadTarget_)
| extend Hostname = trim_end(@"\..+", DeviceName)
| project
    TimeGenerated,
    DeviceName,
    Hostname,
    InitiatingProcessAccountName,
    DownloadTarget_,
    InitiatingProcessCommandLine,
    InitiatingProcessParentFileName,
    Description_

alertDetailsOverride.alertDescriptionFormat:
{{Description_}}

The use of DownloadString in a powershell command can be indicative of attempts to download and execute malicious code using native windows binaries. 

Handling Guidance: Examine the user and download target to identify if this is a permitted activity, or a sign of post-exploitation behavior Also look at other activities performed by the user after this command was run to look for the signs of malicious activity.
